# Affirm DESIGN.md Applicator

Generate and modify UI code that matches Affirm's design system as defined in `DESIGN.md` (located at `.cursor/rules/DESIGN.md`). This rule ensures every piece of generated UI uses the authoritative design tokens extracted from the DS Core Library Figma file.

## When to Use

- Building new UI components, pages, or screens
- Modifying existing UI to match Affirm's brand
- Reviewing generated UI for design system compliance
- Prototyping outside of the main Affirm codebases
- Any time the user says "apply design system", "use DESIGN.md", "match Affirm style", or asks to build UI

## Project Context

This is a **standalone Vite + React prototype** (`afrm-payrescue`). The project uses CSS Modules with design tokens defined in `src/styles/tokens.css`. Always:
- Reference existing tokens like `var(--components-color-background-interactive-default)`, `var(--font-family-display)`, etc.
- Prefer token references over raw hex values in component CSS Modules
- When no token exists for a value, use the raw hex from DESIGN.md directly in CSS

## Apply Design Tokens

When generating any UI code, apply these rules in order:

### Colors
1. Primary button background: `#000049` → `var(--components-color-background-interactive-default)` — NEVER `#8C8CFF`
2. Page background: `#f8f8fa` → `var(--components-color-background-secondary)`
3. Primary text: `#121319` → `var(--components-color-foreground-primary)` — never pure black
4. Link text: `#1b0d7c` (use directly, no token alias exists)
5. Border primary: `#cccdd4` → `var(--components-color-border-default)`
6. Brand accent: `#4a4af4`

### Typography
1. Headlines: `var(--font-family-display)` = `'Axiforma for Affirm'` with SF Pro fallbacks
2. Body: `var(--font-family-body)` = `'Calibre'` with SF Pro fallbacks
3. Minimum body: 16px (`var(--semantic-size-body-medium)`)
4. Headlines use negative letter-spacing (-0.25px at 24px, -0.5px at 32px, -1px at 40px+)
5. `headline-Small` (18px, weight 700) is the ONLY place Bold (700) is allowed

### Spacing (use existing tokens)
- Page margins: 16px = `var(--components-spacing-md)`
- Page vertical: 32px = `var(--components-spacing-xl)`
- Card padding: 16px = `var(--components-spacing-md)`
- Dialog padding: 24px = `var(--components-spacing-lg)`

### Border Radius (use existing tokens)
- Buttons: pill → `border-radius: 100px` (already set globally in `Button.module.css`)
- Cards on page: 16px = `var(--radius-onpage-default)`
- Cards on surface / inputs: 8px = `var(--radius-onsurface-default)`
- Dialogs/modals: 24px = `var(--radius-elevatedsurface-default)`
- Inset elements: 2px = `var(--radius-onsurface-inset)`

### Elevation
1. Default: NO shadow. Use background color layering via the bg tokens
2. No box-shadow on cards or containers

## Reflex Patterns to Reject

Match-and-refuse — if about to write any of these, stop and use the Affirm equivalent:

- `#8C8CFF`, `#a5a5ff` as primary button → use `#000049` / `var(--components-color-background-interactive-default)`
- `#7c3aed`, `#6366f1`, `#4f46e5` as primary CTA → `#000049`
- Any `linear-gradient(...)` on page body, hero, or card → flat surface tokens
- `box-shadow` on cards or containers → use bg color layering
- `border-radius: 4px / 6px / 8px` on buttons → pill (100px)
- Pure white `#ffffff` as page body background → `var(--components-color-background-secondary)` = `#f8f8fa`
- `#000`, `#000000`, `#212121` for body text → `var(--components-color-foreground-primary)` = `#121319`
- `font-family: Inter` → use `var(--font-family-body)` (Calibre)
- `font-family: Arial` / `Helvetica` / bare `system-ui` → use `var(--font-family-display)` or `var(--font-family-body)`
- `text-transform: uppercase` + bold on form labels → sentence-case Medium-weight
- `font-weight: 700` on body text → Semibold (600) maximum; Bold only for `headline-Small`
- Arbitrary spacing (15px, 18px, 25px, 30px) → use token values (8, 12, 16, 24, 32px)
- `border-radius` < 18px on buttons → pill
- Gradients as page or card backgrounds → flat

## The Affirm Slop Test

Before handing off any UI, run this gut check:

> If you showed this to an Affirm employee and said "this is from our product," would they believe you?

The fingerprint is: deep indigo `#000049`, flat layered neutrals (no shadows), pill buttons (100px radius), Calibre/Axiforma. If those four things aren't immediately present, the test fails.

